-- PRESS DIGEST - Russia - Oct 2
-- 
-- Thu Oct 02, 2014 05:15AM EDT
-- None



MOSCOW, Oct 2 (Reuters) - The following are some of the stories in Russia's newspapers on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

VEDOMOSTI www.vedomosti.ru - Finance Minister Anton Siluanov is suggesting employees should share with business the tax burden for the social sector, including spending on medicine and pension savings. - State statistics agency Rosstat has reported consumer price growth in September at 0.7 percent which means annual inflation of 8.1 percent. This is the maximum level recorded since 2011, the daily says. - The daily suggests that the state might be interested in acquiring Igor Zyuzin's stake in the Mechel steelmaker and coal-mining group. - Martin Gilman, a member of Sberbank's <SBER.MM> supervisory board, is said to have invested 2.3 million roubles ($58,000) in purchasing 0.00014 percent of ordinary shares of the state lender. - Russia's state bank VTB <VTBR.MM> is apparently in talks with its European counterparts on launching consumer loans in Germany and Austria in 2015.KOMMERSANT www.kommersant.ru - President Vladimir Putin has assured Russia's Internet users that the state has no plans to restrict access to the global network. - Russia's anti-monopoly watchdog has warned Rosneft <ROSN.MM> and Gazprom Neft against putting restrictions on oil supplies to independent oil traders in Moscow and its far eastern regions.- The government confirmed on Wednesday Russia's withdrawal from the international educational Future Leaders Exchange project. - Russia's state run Social Insurance Fund is ready to spend up to 2 million roubles on financing Crimea's recreation facilities to encourage no less than 35,000 people to spend their vacations in the region by the end of the year.  IZVESTIA www.izvestia.ru - Russian lawmakers are considering an amnesty for those businesses which are ready to return their capital to Russia from off-shore companies. - Russia will insist on the resumption of an investigation into the reasons for the crash of Malaysia's Boeing in Ukraine during a conference to be held in Geneva.  ROSSIISKAYA GAZETA www.rg.ru -  Russia has almost completed the formation of its first Arctic motorised infantry brigade to be located in Murmansk and will deploy the second one in Yamal-Nenetsk region by 2016, chief commander of the land forces Oleg Salyukov said on Wednesday.